# Functions ðŸ”§

A function is a block of code designed to perform a particular task.

It is executed when something invokes it (calls it).

```javascript
function greet(name) {
  return "Hello " + name;
}

let message = greet("Alice");
console.log(message); // "Hello Alice"
```

# Function Declaration ðŸ—£ï¸

Declared with the `function` keyword.

Declarations are **hoisted**, meaning you can call them before they are defined.

```javascript
// This works!
sayHi();

function sayHi() {
  console.log("Hi!");
}
```

# Function Expression ðŸ¤

A function can also be defined using an expression and stored in a variable.

These are **not** hoisted.

```javascript
const x = function (a, b) {
    return a * b
};

let z = x(4, 3);
```

# Arrow Functions ðŸ¹

Introduced in ES6, arrow functions allow a shorter syntax.

```javascript
// Old way
const hello = function() {
  return "Hello World!";
}

// Arrow Function
const hello = () => {
  return "Hello World!";
}

// Even Shorter (Implicit Return)
const hello = () => "Hello World!";
```

> âš ï¸ **Note:** They do not have their own `this` binding.

# Parameters vs Arguments ðŸ“¥

- **Parameters:** The names listed in the function definition.
- **Arguments:** The real values passed to the function.

```javascript
// name is a parameter
function welcome(name) {
  console.log(name);
}

// "John" is an argument
welcome("John");
```

## Default Parameters (ES6)
```javascript
function myFunction(x, y = 10) {
  return x + y;
}
```

# Scope ðŸ”­

Scope determines the accessibility (visibility) of variables.

## Local Scope
Variables declared within a JavaScript function become **local** to the function.

```javascript
function myFunction() {
  let carName = "Volvo";
  // code here CAN use carName
}
// code here can NOT use carName
```

# Global Scope ðŸŒ

A variable declared outside a function becomes **global**.

```javascript
let carName = "Volvo";
// code here can use carName

function myFunction() {
  // code here can also use carName
}
```

> âš ï¸ **Warning:** Avoid polluting the global scope. It can lead to naming conflicts.
